docs.abstract: Carlos Delgado remembered the difficulty of demonstrating alone 16 years ago. Now, he and current players are encouraged by a growing sense of solidarity with Black athletes.
docs.snippet: Carlos Delgado remembered the difficulty of demonstrating alone 16 years ago. Now, he and current players are encouraged by a growing sense of solidarity with Black athletes.
docs.lead_paragraph: Carlos Delgado, the former Toronto Blue Jays and Mets slugger, was playing basketball with his 13-year-old son at their home in Puerto Rico on Wednesday evening when he noticed a news alert on his phone: The Milwaukee Bucks players were sitting out of their N.B.A. playoff game to protest systemic racism and police brutality following the shooting of Jacob Blake, a Black man, by police in Kenosha, Wis.

headline.main: After a Long Lull, Protesting Is Taking Hold Across Baseball
headline.print_headline: After a Long Lull, Protesting Becomes Popular Again in Baseball

docs.abstract: The Dodgers are 22-8 after 30 games of a 60-game season that will be remembered for postponed games, health-driven rules and expanded playoffs.
docs.snippet: The Dodgers are 22-8 after 30 games of a 60-game season that will be remembered for postponed games, health-driven rules and expanded playoffs.
docs.lead_paragraph: The logo of the 2020 All-Star Game looms over the action at Dodger Stadium from a billboard above the right-field pavilion. The game was supposed to be held last month in Los Angeles, for the first time in 40 years, but the coronavirus pandemic canceled it.

headline.main: Baseball’s Most Unusual Season Is Halfway Over
headline.print_headline: Halfway Through a Fully Weird Season

docs.abstract: The Mets’ limited coronavirus infection showed it was probably inevitable it would hit a New York team. When they return, though, they are a team worth watching.
docs.snippet: The Mets’ limited coronavirus infection showed it was probably inevitable it would hit a New York team. When they return, though, they are a team worth watching.
docs.lead_paragraph: Health is paramount, of course, and not the usual kind of health we talk about with the Mets. Two members of their traveling party tested positive for the coronavirus on Thursday — one player and one staff member — and Major League Baseball has paused their season in an effort to prevent the spread.

headline.main: Baseball’s New Game Plan: Wait a Few Days and Hope for Good Health
headline.print_headline: New Game Plan: Wait, and Hope For Good Health

docs.abstract: Fernando Tatis Jr.’s grand slam with a big lead set off a new round of pearl-clutching. But even he didn’t understand what he had done wrong.

docs.lead_paragraph: Earlier this week, Fernando Tatis Jr. of the San Diego Padres hit a grand slam, a seemingly exciting moment for player, fans and teammates.

headline.main: Baseball’s Unwritten Rules: Where Does It Say You Can’t Do That?
headline.print_headline: Whatever You Do, Don’t Break an Unwritten Rule

docs.abstract: San Diego dealt 16 players and acquired nine major leaguers in a rush of deals before Monday’s trading deadline, hoping to challenge the perennial division favorites in Los Angeles.
docs.snippet: San Diego dealt 16 players and acquired nine major leaguers in a rush of deals before Monday’s trading deadline, hoping to challenge the perennial division favorites in Los Angeles.
docs.lead_paragraph: As he canvassed the major leagues before Monday’s trading deadline, A.J. Preller even spoke with Andrew Friedman, his chief rival in the National League West. Friedman runs baseball operations for the Los Angeles Dodgers, the team that has it all. Preller is the general manager of the San Diego Padres, their historically hapless neighbor.

headline.main: The Padres Bulk Up and Set Their Sights on Catching the Dodgers
headline.print_headline: Padres, Hoping to Meet a Rare Moment, Load Up

docs.abstract: There’s no denying his charm and genuine passion for baseball. But his habit of overstepping boundaries would have made him an uncomfortable presence if he had succeeded in purchasing the Mets.
docs.snippet: There’s no denying his charm and genuine passion for baseball. But his habit of overstepping boundaries would have made him an uncomfortable presence if he had succeeded in purchasing the Mets.
docs.lead_paragraph: From the very start, Alex Rodriguez has been an achiever. He was the first overall draft pick at 17 years old and a batting champion at 21. He was the richest player in baseball at 25 and a three-time most valuable player at 32.

headline.main: Denying Alex Rodriguez, Mets Avoid a Risky Presence in the Owner’s Box
headline.print_headline: Rodriguez’s Missteps Stall His Climb to the Owner’s Box

docs.abstract: A strange season continued as the Yankees and Mets ended a five-game weekend series at Yankee Stadium on Sunday with two extra-inning games, though each of them lasted only eight innings.
docs.snippet: A strange season continued as the Yankees and Mets ended a five-game weekend series at Yankee Stadium on Sunday with two extra-inning games, though each of them lasted only eight innings.
docs.lead_paragraph: If you had somehow forgotten the uniqueness of the 2020 Major League Baseball season, the Yankees’ weekend series against the Mets had plenty of reminders. They played five games in three days at Yankee Stadium after a Mets player and staff member tested positive for the coronavirus, forcing a postponement of the previous weekend’s series at Citi Field.

headline.main: It’s Confusing Sometimes, but the Yankees Manage to Stay on Track
headline.print_headline: A Confusing Season for the Yanks, Whether Looking Back or Looking Ahead

docs.abstract: The Mets’ Brodie Van Wagenen criticized Rob Manfred’s handling of player protests in comments captured on a video stream. The Mets were one of many teams that opted not to play Thursday.
docs.snippet: The Mets’ Brodie Van Wagenen criticized Rob Manfred’s handling of player protests in comments captured on a video stream. The Mets were one of many teams that opted not to play Thursday.
docs.lead_paragraph: The Mets and the Miami Marlins chose not to play on Thursday, joining 12 other Major League Baseball teams in sitting out in response to the police shooting of a Black man in Kenosha, Wis.

headline.main: Mets G.M. Rebukes Commissioner but Apologizes, Citing Misunderstanding
headline.print_headline: Mets’ G.M. Says Manfred ‘Doesn’t Get It,’ but Apologizes

docs.abstract: Lucas Giolito of the White Sox struck out 13 Pirates and won, 1-0, in the best performance of baseball’s restarted season.
docs.snippet: Lucas Giolito of the White Sox struck out 13 Pirates and won, 1-0, in the best performance of baseball’s restarted season.
docs.lead_paragraph: The grim line of numbers is frozen forever, a monument to the depths of professional despair for Lucas Giolito of the Chicago White Sox. In 2018, he had a 6.13 earned run average with 90 walks. It is very hard to be that bad and stay in the majors.

headline.main: A Rebuilt Pitcher Puts Together the Season’s First No-Hitter
headline.print_headline: No Hits, No Runs, No Fans There to See It

docs.abstract: It was the first no-hitter of the pandemic-delayed major league season.
docs.snippet: It was the first no-hitter of the pandemic-delayed major league season.
docs.lead_paragraph: CHICAGO — Lucas Giolito pitched the first no-hitter of the pandemic-delayed major league season, striking out 13 and permitting just one runner in leading the Chicago White Sox over the Pittsburgh Pirates, 4-0, Tuesday night.

headline.main: Lucas Giolito Throws a No-Hitter for the White Sox
headline.print_headline: No-Hitter For Giolito Of White Sox
